  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> So your solution would be to use \".ais-hierarchical-menu--list .ais-hierarchical-menu--list\" style then remove the style with selectors like \".ais-hierarchical-menu--list .ais-hierarchical-menu--list .ais-hierarchical-menu--list\"?\n\nYes. You override rules with more specific selectors. This is the `C` of `CSS` :)\n\nIn that specific case, most of the rules will be shared between the parent and child lists, but a few adjustements on padding/size/color will be needed, so it make sense to override the rules of the parent with those of the child.\n\nI agree that providing the `-lvl` classes will make things easier and we should do it. I was just suggesting the usual way to do that (more an enhancement than a bug I mean).\n",
